               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary><p>An account of <persName xml:lang="ta">Maturai Vīraṉ</persName>, a 17th century deity of protection. Written sometimes as individual lines of praise that end with <foreign xml:lang="ta">ē</foreign> vowel in order to rhyme, and sometimes in prose.</p>
<p>The story is about the origin of <persName xml:lang="ta">Maturai Vīraṉ</persName>, a <foreign xml:lang="ta">kāval teyvam</foreign>. It also lists out the various deeds he performed to protect the people of Maturai.</p>
<p>The first few folios (<locus facs="5">U1</locus> up to <locus facs="11">U4</locus>) consisting of invocatory content are by various hands.</p>

<p>The manuscript appears incomplete, since no verses of exaltation are to be found in the end. The text moreover ends abruptly.</p>
</summary>
                  
